'''''Sammy Lightfoot''''' is a video game written by Warren Schwader for the [[Apple II]] and published by [[Sierra Entertainment|Sierra On-Line]] in 1983.<ref name=giantlist/>  It is a multi-screen [[platform game]] (or "climbing game", as the genre was called in the US in 1983),<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Player's Guide to Climbing Games |journal=Electronic Games |date=January 1983 |volume=1 |issue=11 |page=49 |url=https://archive.org/stream/Electronic_Games_Volume_01_Number_11_1983-01_Reese_Communications_US#page/n47/mode/2up}}</ref> in the vein of ''[[Donkey Kong (arcade game)|Donkey Kong]]''. ''Sammy Lightfoot'' follows the travails of a circus worker who jumps and climbs through a number of perilous situations. It was initially ported to the [[Commodore 64]]<ref>{{Lemon64 game|id=2212|name=Sammy Lightfoot}}</ref> followed by [[ColecoVision]]<ref>[http://www.rarityguide.com/colecovision_view.php ColecoVision Rarity Guide]</ref> and the [[PC-8800 series]].

==Reception==
''The Commodore 64 Home Companion'' stated that ''Sammy Lightfoot'' captures the cartoon spirit and graphic style of ''Donkey Kong'' without being a simple donkey clone".<ref name=C64HC>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/The_Commodore_64_Home_Companion#page/n175/mode/2up|first=George | last = Beekman | title=Sierra On-Line|work=The Commodore 64 Home Companion|year=1984|access-date=August 19, 2016|pages=174â€“175}}</ref>

